issue.title: Support newer setuptools
issue.body:
I have been using flexget using pip installs for a while.

I upgraded my setuptools and I get this warning:

```
ERROR: pip's dependency resolver does not currently take into account all the packages that are installed. This behaviour is the source of the following dependency conflicts.
flexget 3.8.0 requires setuptools==65.6.3; python_version >= "3.7" and python_version < "4.0", but you have setuptools 68.2.2 which is incompatible.

```

Everything still seems to work fine, but the dependencies expect a certain version of setup tools. Any chance this can be updated?

issue.title: docker container - add ability to pull more python modules from PIP_REQUIREMENTS_FILE environment variable
issue.body:
### Expected behaviour:

The plex_watchlist plugin should work seamlessly as documented, as well as other plugins that have requirements
the developers have deliberately not chosen to include in the default requirements.txt.

### Actual behaviour:

```
2023-02-11 16:55:09 CRITICAL task          discover-plex-watchlist-movies plexapi package required
```

### Steps to reproduce:

- Step 1: Configure the plex watchlist feature in `config.yml`

```yaml
  discover-plex-watchlist-movies:
    priority: 49
    no_entries_ok: yes
    plex_watchlist:
      token: '{? plex.token ?}'
      type: movie
    accept_all: yes
    seen: local
    list_add:
      - movie_list: movies
```

- Step 2: execute the task

```
flexget execute --tasks discover-plex-watchlist-movies --now
```

#### Config:

You don't need my full config, it's irrelevant, the problem is that the plex_watchlist plugin requires the plexapi
python module and the developers deliberately chose to not include it in requirements.txt

```yaml
  discover-plex-watchlist-movies:
    priority: 49
    no_entries_ok: yes
    plex_watchlist:
      token: '{? plex.token ?}'
      type: movie
    accept_all: yes
    seen: local
    list_add:
      - movie_list: movies
```
  
#### Log:

<details>
 <summary>(click to expand)</summary>

```
2023-02-11 16:55:09 CRITICAL task          discover-plex-watchlist-movies plexapi package required
```
</details>

### Additional information:

- FlexGet version: 3.5.22
- Python version: 3.10.10
- Installation method: docker
- Using daemon (yes/no): yes (irrelevant)
- OS and version: docker current as of 2022-02-12

### Proposed fix:

Look at cpoppema/docker-flexget. He has some very cute [code](https://github.com/cpoppema/docker-flexget/blob/83ad55804c17d05aa5af209296665f7c58fdb24d/etc/cont-init.d/20-update-flexget) that looks at the environment variable `PIP_REQUIREMENTS_FILE` installs additional python modules.

This could go in etc/cont-init.d/ if we used s6 supervisor
```
if [ ! -z "$PIP_REQUIREMENTS_FILE" ]; then
    while IFS= read -r line; do
        if [ ! -z "$line" ] && [[ "$line" != \#* ]]; then
            pip install -U "$line"
        fi
    done < "$PIP_REQUIREMENTS_FILE"
fi
```

Another alternative, is look for the environment variable "FLEXGET_EXTRA_MODULES" which could be a comma-separated collection of modules, and install them that way. I suggest the former so it makes versioning and pinning cleaner, but don't really care strongly.

This is a pretty trivial and easy to fix problem, but I don't have a good build env to test it on.

comment.body:
Quality doesn't accept entries, just rejects the ones that don't match it.
`accept_all: no` is irrelevant BTW, entries are undecided by default.

comment.body:
> Yes, for an entry to pass the filter phase, at least one plugin must accept it, and no plugins can reject it. The normal paradigm is to have one main plugin that does the accepting, (e.g. imdb, series, list_match,) and possibly other plugins that do rejecting to further filter down the list (e.g. quality, content_size, regexp.)

New problem comes up.

When I wrote my task as you recommended.
```
tasks: 
  BDMru: 
    rss: https://kp.m-team.cc/torrentrss.php?https=1&rows=10&cat419=1&sta1=1&tea6=1&linktype=dl&passkey=
    accept_all: no
    quality: 1080p
    download: /RssTorrents/BDMru
```
The log said:
```
Task didn't produce any entries. This is likely due to a mis-configured or non-functional input.
```

It seems the "quality" filter doesn't work at all. Is the format of the RSS not compatable with the filter "quality"? What does "quality" filter base on? Title of each RSS items? I am sure these titles do contain the key word "1080p".
